---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const contactEmail = import.meta.env.PUBLIC_CONTACT_EMAIL ?? "admin@pricingnest.com";
---
<BaseLayout title="Contact | PricingNest" description="Editorial contact, correction requests, and calculator feedback details for PricingNest.">
  <section class="hero">
    <h1>Contact</h1>
    <p>
      Use this page for calculator feedback, correction requests, unclear methodology notes, or suggestions for a better
      guide or example.
    </p>
    <p class="muted">
      If you want to read how reviews are handled first, see <a href="/methodology/">Methodology</a>.
    </p>
    <p class="muted">
      Email: <a href={`mailto:${contactEmail}`}>{contactEmail}</a>
    </p>
    <p style="margin-top: 0.75rem;">
      Use this email for calculator feedback, data corrections, or new tool requests. If you are asking about pricing
      models, include your unit definition (calls, events, GB, seats), expected monthly volume, and any major cost drivers
      (infra, vendors, support). That context helps us point you to the right calculator or guide and update assumptions
      when needed. We also welcome notes about confusing terminology, missing use cases, or examples you want to see in the
      guides.
      </p>
      <p class="muted" style="margin-top: 0.75rem;">
        Typical response time is 1-2 business days. Please avoid sharing confidential data; summary inputs are enough for us
        to validate formulas and improve the toolkit.
      </p>

      <div class="grid" style="margin-top: 1rem;">
        <section class="card col8">
          <h2>Editorial contact</h2>
          <p class="muted">
            This inbox is the editorial contact for PricingNest. Use it for calculator feedback, navigation issues,
            confusing explanations, and updates that affect retained tools, guides, glossary pages, or the methodology
            itself.
          </p>

          <h2 style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">Correction requests</h2>
          <p class="muted">
            If you believe a formula, assumption, default example, interpretation note, or linked source is wrong or
            unclear, send a correction request. We use these reports to review retained pages and refresh trust-critical
            wording when needed.
          </p>

          <h2 style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">What happens next</h2>
          <p class="muted">
            We review the page, compare the feedback against the current model or explanation, and decide whether the fix
            belongs in a calculator, a guide, a glossary entry, or a policy page. If the change affects the substance of a
            retained page, we update the visible review date when appropriate.
          </p>

          <h2 style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">What to include</h2>
          <ul class="list">
            <li>The page URL you are referring to.</li>
            <li>The exact formula, assumption, example, or paragraph that looks wrong or incomplete.</li>
            <li>Your suggested correction or the missing context you think the page needs.</li>
            <li>Any non-confidential usage, pricing, or cost context that helps explain the issue.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

      <aside class="card col4">
        <h2>What we can review</h2>
        <ul class="list">
          <li>Calculator logic and default assumptions.</li>
          <li>Explanatory copy on retained tool pages.</li>
          <li>Guide and glossary wording that creates pricing confusion.</li>
          <li>Broken links, stale references, and unclear next-step guidance.</li>
          <li>Policy pages and approval-critical wording if something looks inconsistent.</li>
          <li>The methodology page if a review rule or trust signal needs to be clearer.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">What we cannot verify for you</h2>
        <ul class="list">
          <li>Your internal margin targets or contract obligations.</li>
          <li>Confidential vendor pricing, usage logs, or legal terms you cannot share.</li>
          <li>Whether a modeled result is the final decision your finance or legal team should approve.</li>
        </ul>
      </aside>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
